","Bolam, Northumberland, England":"Bolam, Northumberland, England","Aydon, Northumberland, England":"Aydon, Northumberland, England","England":"England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England"},"en":{"1197–between 1243 and 1248":"1197–from 1243 to 1248","1194–1236":"1194–1236","1197–1248":"1197–1248","–1248":"–1248","1227–1279":"1227–1279","1167–1206":"1167–1206","1171–1235":"1171–1235","1197":"1197","1194":"1194","1171":"1171","1206":"1206","between 1243 and 1248":"from 1243 to 1248","1227":"1227","1215":"1215","1248":"1248","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1235":"1235","1279":"1279","1167":"1167","about 1227":"about 1227","about 1235":"about 1235","about 1197":"about 1197","Bolam, Northumberland, England":"Bolam, Northumberland, England","Aydon, Northumberland, England":"Aydon, Northumberland, England","England":"England","Northumberland, England":"Northumberland, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Bolam","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (Northumberland): habitational name from any of the places called Bolam in Northumberland and County Durham. These placenames could derive from the dative plural (<i>bolum</i>) of either of two unattested Old English words, <i>bola</i> ‘tree trunk’ (compare Old Norse <i>bolr</i>) or <i>bol</i> ‘rounded hill’ (compare Middle Low German <i>bolle</i> ‘round object’)."],"variants":[{"name":"Bollom","meanings":["English: variant of   Bolam  ."]}]},{"name":"Alice","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Adelaide  , representing an Old French spelling of a reduced form of Germanic <i>Adalheidis</i>. <i>Alice</i> and <i>Adelaide</i> were already regarded as distinct names in English during the medieval period. <i>Alice</i> enjoyed a surge of popularity in the 19th century and periods of favour ever since. It was the name of the central character of  Lewis Carroll's  Alice's Adventures in Wonderland (  1865 ) and Through the Looking Glass (  1872 ), who was based on his child friend  Alice Liddell , daughter of the Dean of Christ Church, Oxford."],"variants":[{"name":"Alys","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Alice ."]},{"name":"Alis","meanings":["equivalent of <b>Alice</b> ."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":18,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":0},{"id":1705188,"age":27,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":0}],"lifeSummary":"When Alice de Bolam was born in 1197, in England, her father, Walter FitzGilbert, was 31 and her mother, Emma Umfraville, was 27